# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: btrfs-filesystem
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Btrfs is intended to address the lack of pooling, snapshots, integrity checking, data scrubbing, and integral multi-device spanning in Linux file systems.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Mason, the principal Btrfs author, stated that its goal was "to let [Linux] scale for the storage that will be available.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Scaling is not just about addressing the storage but also means being able to administer and to manage it with a clean interface that lets people see what's being used and makes it more reliable".
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The core data structure of Btrfs‍—‌the copy-on-write B-tree‍—‌was originally proposed by IBM researcher Ohad Rodeh at a USENIX conference in 2007.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Chris Mason, an engineer working on ReiserFS for SUSE at the time, joined Oracle later that year and began work on a new file system based on B-trees.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] In 2008, the principal developer of the ext3 and ext4 file systems, Theodore Ts'o, stated that although ext4 has improved features, it is not a major advance; it uses old technology and is a stop-gap.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Ts'o said that Btrfs is the better direction because "it offers improvements in scalability, reliability, and ease of management".
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Btrfs also has "a number of the same design ideas that reiser3/4 had".
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Btrfs 1.0, with finalized on-disk format, was originally slated for a late-2008 release, and was finally accepted into the Linux kernel mainline in 2009.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Several Linux distributions began offering Btrfs as an experimental choice of root file system during installation.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] In July 2011, Btrfs automatic defragmentation and scrubbing features were merged into version 3.0 of the Linux kernel mainline.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Besides Mason at Oracle, Miao Xie at Fujitsu contributed performance improvements.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] In June 2012, Mason left Oracle for Fusion-io, which he left a year later with Josef Bacik to join Facebook.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] While at both companies, Mason continued his work on Btrfs.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] In 2012, two Linux distributions moved Btrfs from experimental to production or supported status: Oracle Linux in March, followed by SUSE Linux Enterprise in August.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] In 2015, Btrfs was adopted as the default file system for SUSE Linux Enterprise Server (SLE) 12.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] In August 2017, Red Hat announced in the release notes for Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL) 7.4 that it no longer planned to move Btrfs to a fully supported feature (it's been included as a "technology preview" since RHEL 6 beta) noting that it would remain available in the RHEL 7 release series.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Btrfs was removed from RHEL 8 in May 2019.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] RHEL moved from ext4 in RHEL 6 to XFS in RHEL 7.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] In 2020, Btrfs was selected as the default file system for Fedora 33 for desktop variants.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Btrfs provides a *clone* operation that atomically creates a copy-on-write snapshot of a file.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Such cloned files are sometimes referred to as *reflinks*, in light of the proposed associated Linux kernel system call.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] By cloning, the file system does not create a new link pointing to an existing inode; instead, it creates a new inode that initially shares the same disk blocks with the original file.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] As a result, cloning works only within the boundaries of the same Btrfs file system, but since version 3.6 of the Linux kernel it may cross the boundaries of subvolumes under certain circumstances.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The actual data blocks are not duplicated; at the same time, due to the copy-on-write (CoW) nature of Btrfs, modifications to any of the cloned files are not visible in the original file and vice versa.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Cloning should not be confused with hard links, which are directory entries that associate multiple file names with a single file.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] While hard links can be taken as different names for the same file, cloning in Btrfs provides independent files that initially share all their disk blocks.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Support for this Btrfs feature was added in version 7.5 of the GNU coreutils, via the `--reflink` option to the `cp` command.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] In addition to data cloning (FICLONE), Btrfs also supports out-of-band deduplication via FIDEDUPERANGE.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] This functionality allows two files with (even partially) identical data to share storage.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] A Btrfs subvolume can be thought of as a separate POSIX file namespace, mountable separately by passing `subvol` or `subvolid` options to the `mount(8)` utility.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] It can also be accessed by mounting the top-level subvolume, in which case subvolumes are visible and accessible as its subdirectories.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Subvolumes can be created at any place within the file system hierarchy, and they can also be nested.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Nested subvolumes appear as subdirectories within their parent subvolumes, similarly to the way a top-level subvolume presents its subvolumes as subdirectories.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Deleting a subvolume is not possible until all subvolumes below it in the nesting hierarchy are deleted; as a result, top-level subvolumes cannot be deleted.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Any Btrfs file system always has a default subvolume, which is initially set to be the top-level subvolume, and is mounted by default if no subvolume selection option is passed to `mount`.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The default subvolume can be changed as required.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] A Btrfs snapshot is a subvolume that shares its data (and metadata) with some other subvolume, using Btrfs' copy-on-write capabilities, and modifications to a snapshot are not visible in the original subvolume.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Once a writable snapshot is made, it can be treated as an alternate version of the original file system.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] For example, to roll back to a snapshot, a modified original subvolume needs to be unmounted and the snapshot needs to be mounted in its place.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] At that point, the original subvolume may also be deleted.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The copy-on-write (CoW) nature of Btrfs means that snapshots are quickly created, while initially consuming very little disk space.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Since a snapshot is a subvolume, creating nested snapshots is also possible.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Taking snapshots of a subvolume is not a recursive process; thus, if a snapshot of a subvolume is created, every subvolume or snapshot that the subvolume already contains is mapped to an empty directory of the same name inside the snapshot.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Taking snapshots of a directory is not possible, as only subvolumes can have snapshots.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] However, there is a workaround that involves reflinks spread across subvolumes: a new subvolume is created, containing cross-subvolume reflinks to the content of the targeted directory.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Having that available, a snapshot of this new volume can be created.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] A subvolume in Btrfs is quite different from a traditional Logical Volume Manager (LVM) logical volume.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] With LVM, a logical volume is a separate block device, while a Btrfs subvolume is not and it cannot be treated or used that way.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Making dd or LVM snapshots of btrfs leads to data loss if either the original or the copy is mounted while both are on the same computer.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Given any pair of subvolumes (or snapshots), Btrfs can generate a binary diff between them (by using the `btrfs send` command) that can be replayed later (by using `btrfs receive`), possibly on a different Btrfs file system.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The send–receive feature effectively creates (and applies) a set of data modifications required for converting one subvolume into another.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The send/receive feature can be used with regularly scheduled snapshots for implementing a simple form of file system replication, or for the purpose of performing incremental backups.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] A *quota group* (or *qgroup*) imposes an upper limit to the space a subvolume or snapshot may consume.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] A new snapshot initially consumes no quota because its data is shared with its parent, but thereafter incurs a charge for new files and copy-on-write operations on existing files.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] When quotas are active, a quota group is automatically created with each new subvolume or snapshot.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] These initial quota groups are building blocks which can be grouped (with the `btrfs qgroup` command) into hierarchies to implement quota pools.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Quota groups only apply to subvolumes and snapshots, while having quotas enforced on individual subdirectories, users, or user groups is not possible.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] However, workarounds are possible by using different subvolumes for all users or user groups that require a quota to be enforced.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] As the result of having very little metadata anchored in fixed locations, Btrfs can warp to fit unusual spatial layouts of the backend storage devices.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The `btrfs-convert` tool exploits this ability to do an in-place conversion of an ext2/3/4 or ReiserFS file system, by nesting the equivalent Btrfs metadata in its unallocated space—while preserving an unmodified copy of the original file system.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The conversion involves creating a copy of the whole ext2/3/4 metadata, while the Btrfs files simply point to the same blocks used by the ext2/3/4 files.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] This makes the bulk of the blocks shared between the two file systems before the conversion becomes permanent.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Thanks to the copy-on-write nature of Btrfs, the original versions of the file data blocks are preserved during all file modifications.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Until the conversion becomes permanent, only the blocks that were marked as free in ext2/3/4 are used to hold new Btrfs modifications, meaning that the conversion can be undone at any time (although doing so will erase any changes made after the conversion to Btrfs).
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] All converted files are available and writable in the default subvolume of the Btrfs.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] A sparse file holding all of the references to the original ext2/3/4 file system is created in a separate subvolume, which is mountable on its own as a read-only disk image, allowing both original and converted file systems to be accessed at the same time.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Deleting this sparse file frees up the space and makes the conversion permanent.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] In 4.x versions of the mainline Linux kernel, the in-place ext3/4 conversion was considered untested and rarely used.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] However, the feature was rewritten from scratch in 2016 for `btrfs-progs` 4.6. and has been considered stable since then.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] In-place conversion from ReiserFS was introduced in September 2017 with kernel 4.13.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] When creating a new Btrfs, an existing Btrfs can be used as a read-only "seed" file system.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The new file system will then act as a copy-on-write overlay on the seed, as a form of union mounting.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The seed can be later detached from the Btrfs, at which point the rebalancer will simply copy over any seed data still referenced by the new file system before detaching.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] In his 2009 interview, Mason stated that support for encryption was planned for Btrfs.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] In the meantime, a workaround for combining encryption with Btrfs is to use a full-disk encryption mechanism such as dm-crypt / LUKS on the underlying devices and to create the Btrfs file system on top of that layer.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] As of 2020, the developers were working to add keyed hash like HMAC (SHA256).
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Unix systems traditionally rely on "fsck" programs to check and repair file systems.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] This functionality is implemented via the `btrfs check` program.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Since version 4.0 this functionality is deemed relatively stable.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] However, as of December 2022, the btrfs documentation suggests that its `--repair` option be used only if you have been advised by "a developer or an experienced user".
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] As of August 2022, the SLE documentation recommends using a Live CD, performing a backup and only using the repair option as a last resort.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] There is another tool, named `btrfs-restore`, that can be used to recover files from an unmountable file system, without modifying the broken file system itself (i.e., non-destructively).
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] In normal use, Btrfs is mostly self-healing and can recover from broken root trees at mount time, thanks to making periodic data flushes to permanent storage, by default every 30 seconds.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Thus, isolated errors will cause a maximum of 30 seconds of file-system changes to be lost at the next mount.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] This period can be changed by specifying a desired value (in seconds) with the `commit` mount option.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] He suggested instead a modified B-tree (which has no leaf linkage), with a refcount associated to each tree node but stored in an ad hoc free map structure and certain relaxations to the tree's balancing algorithms to make them copy-on-write friendly.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The result would be a data structure suitable for a high-performance object store that could perform copy-on-write snapshots, while maintaining good concurrency.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] At Oracle later that year, Mason began work on a snapshot-capable file system that would use this data structure almost exclusively—not just for metadata and file data, but also recursively to track space allocation of the trees themselves.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] This allowed all traversal and modifications to be funneled through a single code path, against which features such as copy on write, checksumming and mirroring needed to be implemented only once to benefit the entire file system.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Btrfs is structured as several layers of such trees, all using the same B-tree implementation.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The trees store generic *items* sorted by a 136-bit key.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The most significant 64 bits of the key are a unique *object id*.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The middle eight bits are an item type field: its use is hardwired into code as an item filter in tree lookups.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] *Objects* can have multiple items of multiple types.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The remaining (least significant) 64 bits are used in type-specific ways.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Therefore, items for the same object end up adjacent to each other in the tree, grouped by type.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] By choosing certain key values, objects can further put items of the same type in a particular order.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Interior tree nodes are simply flat lists of key-pointer pairs, where the pointer is the logical block number of a child node.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Leaf nodes contain item keys packed into the front of the node and item data packed into the end, with the two growing toward each other as the leaf fills up.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Within each directory, directory entries appear as *directory items*, whose least significant bits of key values are a CRC32C hash of their filename.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Their data is a *location key*, or the key of the inode item it points to.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Directory items together can thus act as an index for path-to-inode lookups, but are not used for iteration because they are sorted by their hash, effectively randomly permuting them.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] To avoid this, each directory entry has a *directory index item*, whose key value of the item is set to a per-directory counter that increments with each new directory entry.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Iteration over these index items thus returns entries in roughly the same order as stored on disk.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Files with hard links in multiple directories have multiple reference items, one for each parent directory.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Files with multiple hard links in the *same* directory pack all of the links' filenames into the same reference item.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] This was a design flaw that limited the number of same-directory hard links to however many could fit in a single tree block.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] (On the default block size of 4 KiB, an average filename length of 8 bytes and a per-filename header of 4 bytes, this would be less than 350.) Applications which made heavy use of multiple same-directory hard links, such as git, GNUS, GMame and BackupPC were observed to fail at this limit.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The limit was eventually removed (and as of October 2012 has been merged pending release in Linux 3.7 ) by introducing spillover *extended reference items* to hold hard link filenames which do not otherwise fit.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] File data is kept outside the tree in extents, which are contiguous runs of disk data blocks.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The item's key offset is the starting byte of the extent.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Snapshots and cloned files share extents.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] When a small part of a large such extent is overwritten, the resulting copy-on-write may create three new extents: a small one containing the overwritten data, and two large ones with unmodified data on either side of the overwrite.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] To avoid having to re-write unmodified data, the copy-on-write may instead create *bookend extents*, or extents which are simply slices of existing extents.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Extent data items allow for this by including an offset into the extent they are tracking: items for bookends are those with non-zero offsets.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The *extent allocation tree* acts as an allocation map for the file system.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Unlike other trees, items in this tree do not have object ids.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] They represent regions of space: their key values hold the starting offsets and lengths of the regions they represent.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The file system divides its allocated space into *block groups* which are variable-sized allocation regions that alternate between preferring metadata extents (tree nodes) and data extents (file contents).
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The default ratio of data to metadata block groups is 1:2.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] They are intended to use concepts of the Orlov block allocator to allocate related files together and resist fragmentation by leaving free space between groups.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] (Ext3 block groups, however, have fixed locations computed from the size of the file system, whereas those in Btrfs are dynamic and created as needed.) Each block group is associated with a *block group item*.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Inode items in the file system tree include a reference to their current block group.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The extent allocation tree, as with all other trees in the file system, is copy-on-write.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Writes to the file system may thus cause a cascade whereby changed tree nodes and file data result in new extents being allocated, causing the extent tree itself to change.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] To avoid creating a feedback loop, extent tree nodes which are still in memory but not yet committed to disk may be updated in place to reflect new copied-on-write extents.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] In theory, the extent allocation tree makes a conventional free-space bitmap unnecessary because the extent allocation tree acts as a B-tree version of a BSP tree.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] In practice, however, an in-memory red–black tree of page-sized bitmaps is used to speed up allocations.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] These bitmaps are persisted to disk (starting in Linux 2.6.37, via the `space_cache` mount option) as special extents that are exempt from checksumming and copy-on-write.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] CRC-32C checksums are computed for both data and metadata and stored as *checksum items* in a *checksum tree*.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] There is room for 256 bits of metadata checksums and up to a full node (roughly 4 KB or more) for data checksums.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Btrfs has provisions for additional checksum algorithms to be added in future versions of the file system.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] There is one checksum item per contiguous run of allocated blocks, with per-block checksums packed end-to-end into the item data.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] If there are more checksums than can fit, they spill into another checksum item in a new leaf.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] If the file system detects a checksum mismatch while reading a block, it first tries to obtain (or create) a good copy of this block from another device – if internal mirroring or RAID techniques are in use.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Btrfs can initiate an online check of the entire file system by triggering a file system scrub job that is performed in the background.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The scrub job scans the entire file system for integrity and automatically attempts to report and repair any bad blocks it finds along the way.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] To avoid this, a temporary per-subvolume *log tree* is created to journal fsync-triggered copies on write.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Log trees are self-contained, tracking their own extents and keeping their own checksum items.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Their items are replayed and deleted at the next full tree commit or (if there was a system crash) at the next remount.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Block devices are divided into *physical chunks* of 1 GiB for data and 256 MiB for metadata.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Physical chunks across multiple devices can be mirrored or striped together into a single *logical chunk*.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] These logical chunks are combined into a single logical address space that the rest of the file-system uses.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The *chunk tree* tracks this by storing each device therein as a *device item* and logical chunks as *chunk map items*, which provide a forward mapping from logical to physical addresses by storing their offsets in the least significant 64 bits of their key.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Defragmentation, shrinking, and rebalancing operations require extents to be relocated.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] However, doing a simple copy-on-write of the relocating extent will break sharing between snapshots and consume disk space.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] To preserve sharing, an update-and-swap algorithm is used, with a special *relocation tree* serving as scratch space for affected metadata.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] The extent to be relocated is first copied to its destination.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Then, by following backreferences upward through the affected subvolume's file system tree, metadata pointing to the old extent is progressively updated to point at the new one; any newly updated items are stored in the relocation tree.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] Once the update is complete, items in the relocation tree are swapped with their counterparts in the affected subvolume, and the relocation tree is discarded.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] All the file system's trees—including the chunk tree itself—are stored in chunks, creating a potential bootstrapping problem when mounting the file system.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/btrfs] To bootstrap into a mount, a list of physical addresses of chunks belonging to the chunk and root trees are stored in the *superblock*.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] Copy-on-write finds its main use in operating systems, sharing the physical memory of computers running multiple processes, in the implementation of the fork() system call.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] Typically, the new process does not modify any memory and immediately executes a new process, replacing the address space entirely.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] It would waste processor time and memory to copy all of the old process's memory during the fork only to immediately discard the copy.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] Copy-on-write can be implemented efficiently using the page table by marking certain pages of memory as read-only and keeping a count of the number of references to the page.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] When data is written to these pages, the operating-system kernel intercepts the write attempt and allocates a new physical page, initialized with the copy-on-write data, although the allocation can be skipped if there is only one reference.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] The kernel then updates the page table with the new (writable) page, decrements the number of references, and performs the write.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] The new allocation ensures that a change in the memory of one process is not visible in another's.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] The copy-on-write technique can be extended to support efficient memory allocation by keeping one page of physical memory filled with zeros.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] When the memory is allocated, all the pages returned refer to the page of zeros and are all marked copy-on-write.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] This way, physical memory is not allocated for the process until data is written, allowing processes to reserve more virtual memory than physical memory and use memory sparsely, at the risk of running out of virtual address space.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] The combined algorithm is similar to demand paging.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] Copy-on-write pages are also used in the Linux kernel's same-page merging feature.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] COW is also used in library, application, and system code.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] In the PHP programming language, all types except references are implemented as copy-on-write.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] For example, strings and arrays are passed by reference, but when modified, they are duplicated if they have non-zero reference counts.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] This allows them to act as value types without the performance problems of copying on assignment or making them immutable.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] In the Qt framework, many types are copy-on-write ("implicitly shared" in Qt's terms).
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] Qt uses atomic compare-and-swap operations to increment or decrement the internal reference counter.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] Since the copies are cheap, Qt types can often be safely used by multiple threads without the need of locking mechanisms such as mutexes.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] The benefits of COW are thus valid in both single- and multithreaded systems.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] In Docker, a set of software for implementing operating-system level virtualization, docker images are built in a layered format, with lower layers being read-only and the upper layer available for editing.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] Creating a new image which shares the same base layers as another image does not copy the layers, but instead follows COW principles and allows the two images to share layers until one is edited.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] COW is used as the underlying mechanism in file systems like ZFS, Btrfs, ReFS, and Bcachefs, as well as in logical volume management and database servers such as Microsoft SQL Server.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] In traditional file systems, modifying a file overwrites the original data blocks in place.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] In a copy-on-write (COW) file system, the original blocks remain unchanged.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] When part of a file is modified, only the affected blocks are written to new locations, and metadata is updated to point to them, preserving the original version until it’s no longer needed.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] This approach enables features like snapshots, which capture the state of a file at a specific time without consuming much additional space.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] Snapshots typically store only the modified data and are kept close to the original.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] However, they are considered a weak form of incremental backup and cannot replace a full backup.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] In order to create and start new containers quickly, container engines doing OS-level virtualization often perform copy-on-write in storage, either block-level copy-on-write (as described above) or file-level copy-on-write.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] Some but not all filesystems support file-level copy-on-write as part of union mounting, including OverlayFS, aufs, GlusterFS, and UnionFS.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] In computer storage, **logical volume management** (**LVM**) provides a method of allocating space on mass-storage devices that is more flexible than conventional partitioning schemes to store volumes.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] In particular, a volume manager can concatenate, stripe together or otherwise combine partitions (or block devices in general) into larger virtual partitions that administrators can re-size or move, potentially without interrupting system use.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Volume management represents just one of many forms of storage virtualization; its implementation takes place in a layer in the device-driver stack of an operating system (OS) (as opposed to within storage devices or in a network).
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Most volume-manager implementations share the same basic design.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] They start with **physical volumes** (PVs), which can be either hard disks, hard disk partitions, or logical unit numbers (LUNs) of an external storage device.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Volume management treats each PV as being composed of a sequence of chunks called **physical extents** (PEs).
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Some volume managers (such as that in HP-UX and Linux) have PEs of a uniform size; others (such as that in Veritas) have variably-sized PEs that can be split and merged at will.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Normally, PEs simply map one-to-one to **logical extents** (LEs).
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] With mirroring, multiple PEs map to each LE.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] These PEs are drawn from a **physical volume group** (PVG), a set of same-sized PVs which act similarly to hard disks in a RAID 1 array.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] PVGs are usually laid out so that they reside on different disks or data buses for maximum redundancy.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] The system pools LEs into a *volume group* (VG).
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] The pooled LEs can then be concatenated together into virtual disk partitions called **logical volumes** or LVs.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Systems can use LVs as raw block devices just like disk partitions: creating mountable file systems on them, or using them as swap storage.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Striped LVs allocate each successive LE from a different PV; depending on the size of the LE, this can improve performance on large sequential reads by bringing to bear the combined read-throughput of multiple PVs.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Administrators can grow LVs (by concatenating more LEs) or shrink them (by returning LEs to the pool).
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] The concatenated LEs do not have to be contiguous.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] This allows LVs to grow without having to move already-allocated LEs.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Some volume managers allow the re-sizing of LVs in either direction while online.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Changing the size of the LV does not necessarily change the size of a file system on it; it merely changes the size of its containing space.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] A file system that can be resized online is recommended in that it allows the system to adjust its storage on-the-fly without interrupting applications.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] PVs and LVs cannot be shared between or span different VGs (although some volume managers may allow moving them at will between VGs on the same host).
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] This allows administrators conveniently to bring VGs online, to take them offline or to move them between host systems as a single administrative unit.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] VGs can grow their storage pool by absorbing new PVs or shrink by retracting from PVs.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] This may involve moving already-allocated LEs out of the PV.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Most volume managers can perform this movement online; if the underlying hardware is hot-pluggable this allows engineers to upgrade or replace storage without system downtime.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] A hybrid volume is any volume that intentionally and opaquely makes use of two separate physical volumes.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] For instance, a workload may consist of random seeks so an SSD may be used to permanently store frequently used or recently written data, while using higher-capacity rotational magnetic media for long-term storage of rarely needed data.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] On Linux, bcache or dm-cache may be used for this purpose, while Fusion Drive may be used on OS X.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] ZFS also implements this functionality at the file system level, by allowing administrators to configure multi-level read/write caching.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Hybrid volumes present a similar concept as hybrid drives, which also combine solid-state storage and rotational magnetic media.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Some volume managers also implement snapshots by applying copy-on-write to each LE.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] In this scheme, the volume manager will copy the LE to a *copy-on-write table* just before it is written to.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] This preserves an old version of the LV, the snapshot, which may be later reconstructed by overlaying the copy-on-write table atop the current LV.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Unless the volume management supports both thin provisioning and discard, once an LE in the origin volume is written to, it is permanently stored in the snapshot volume.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] If the snapshot volume was made smaller than its origin, which is a common practice, this may render the snapshot inoperable.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Snapshots can be useful for backing up self-consistent versions of volatile data such as table files from a busy database, or for rolling back large changes (such as an operating system upgrade) in a single operation.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Snapshots have a similar effect as rendering storage quiescent, and are similar to the shadow copy (VSS) service in Microsoft Windows.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Some Linux-based Live CDs also use snapshots to simulate read-write access to a read-only optical disc.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Refers to PEs as PPs (physical partitions), and to LEs as LPs (logical partitions).
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Does not have a copy-on-write snapshot mechanism; creates snapshots by freezing one volume of a mirror pair.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] The FreeBSD fast file system (UFS) supports snapshots.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] NetBSD from version 6.0 supports its own re-implementation of Linux LVM.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Re-implementation is based on a BSD licensed device-mapper driver and uses a port of Linux lvm tools as the userspace part of LVM.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] There is no need to support RAID5 in LVM because of NetBSD superior RAIDFrame subsystem.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Refers to PVs as volumes (which can be combined with RAID0, RAID1 or RAID5 primitives into larger volumes), to LVs as soft partitions (which are contiguous extents placeable anywhere on volumes, but which cannot span multiple volumes), and to VGs as disk sets.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Does not have a concept of PEs or LEs; can only RAID0, RAID1, RAID5 or concatenate disk partitions into larger volumes; file systems must span whole volumes.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] ; Software-based RAID is provided by AppleRAID.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Logical volumes can suffer from external fragmentation when the underlying storage devices do not allocate their PEs contiguously.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] This can reduce I/O performance on slow-seeking media such as magnetic disks and other rotational media.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Volume managers that use fixed-size PEs, however, typically make PEs relatively large (for example, Linux LVM uses 4 MB by default) in order to amortize the cost of these seeks.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] With implementations that are solely volume management, such as Core Storage and Linux LVM, separating and abstracting away volume management from the file system loses the ability to easily make storage decisions for particular files or directories.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] For example, if a certain directory (but not the entire file system) is to be permanently moved to faster storage, both the file system layout and the underlying volume management layer need to be traversed.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] For example, on Linux it would be needed to manually determine the offset of a file's contents within a file system and then manually *`pvmove`* the extents (along with data not related to that file) to the faster storage.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/logical-volume-management] Having volume and file management implemented within the same subsystem, instead of having them implemented as separate subsystems, makes the overall process theoretically simpler.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] In computer systems, a **snapshot** is the state of a system at a particular point in time.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] The term was coined as an analogy to that in photography.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] A full backup of a large data set may take a long time to complete.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] On multi-tasking or multi-user systems, there may be writes to that data while it is being backed up.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] This prevents the backup from being atomic and introduces a version skew that may result in data corruption.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] For example, if a user moves a file into a directory that has already been backed up, then that file would be completely missing on the backup media, since the backup operation had already taken place before the addition of the file.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] Version skew may also cause corruption with files which change their size or contents underfoot while being read.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] One approach to safely backing up live data is to temporarily disable write access to data during the backup, either by stopping the accessing applications or by using the locking API provided by the operating system to enforce exclusive read access.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] This is tolerable for low-availability systems (on desktop computers and small workgroup servers, on which regular downtime is acceptable).
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] High-availability 24/7 systems, however, cannot bear service stoppages.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] To avoid downtime, high-availability systems may instead perform the backup on a *snapshot*—a read-only copy of the data set frozen at a point in time—and allow applications to continue writing to their data.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] Most snapshot implementations are efficient and can create snapshots in *O(1)*.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] In other words, the time and I/O needed to create the snapshot does not increase with the size of the data set; by contrast, the time and I/O required for a direct backup is proportional to the size of the data set.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] In some systems once the initial snapshot is taken of a data set, subsequent snapshots copy the changed data only, and use a system of pointers to reference the initial snapshot.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] This method of pointer-based snapshots consumes less disk capacity than if the data set was repeatedly cloned.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] Some Unix systems have snapshot-capable logical volume managers.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] These implement copy-on-write on entire block devices by copying changed blocks‍—‌just before they are to be overwritten within "parent" volumes‍—‌to other storage, thus preserving a self-consistent past image of the block device.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] Filesystems on such snapshot images can later be mounted as if they were on a read-only media.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] Some volume managers also allow creation of *writable* snapshots, extending the copy-on-write approach by disassociating any blocks modified within the snapshot from their "parent" blocks in the original volume.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] Such a scheme could be also described as performing additional copy-on-write operations triggered by the writes to snapshots.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] On Linux, Logical Volume Manager (LVM) allows creation of both read-only and read-write snapshots.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] Writable snapshots were introduced with the LVM version 2 (LVM2).
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] Some file systems, such as WAFL, fossil for Plan 9 from Bell Labs, and ODS-5, internally track old versions of files and make snapshots available through a special namespace.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] Others, like UFS2, provide an operating system API for accessing file histories.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] In NTFS, access to snapshots is provided by the Volume Shadow-copying Service (VSS) in Windows XP and Windows Server 2003 and Shadow Copy in Windows Vista.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] Melio FS provides snapshots via the same VSS interface for shared storage.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] Snapshots have also been available in the NSS (Novell Storage Services) file system on NetWare since version 4.11, and more recently on Linux platforms in the Open Enterprise Server product.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] EMC's Isilon OneFS clustered storage platform implements a single scalable file system that supports read-only snapshots at the file or directory level.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] Any file or directory within the file system can be snapshotted and the system will implement a copy-on-write or point-in-time snapshot dynamically based on which method is determined to be optimal for the system.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] On Linux, the Btrfs and OCFS2 file systems support creating snapshots (cloning) of individual files.
[src:btrfs-filesystem/snapshot-computer-storage] Additionally, Btrfs also supports the creation of snapshots of subvolumes.
